    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-02-16T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-02-16T09:00:00-05:00" n="86"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d86">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851G.00/2–1647: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-02-16T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >February 16, 1947—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>705. I reviewed in some detail yesterday with Ramadier the situation in
                    Indochina, restating our point of view and emphasizing especially the outmoded
                    colonial outlook of many French officials, especially in Saigon. Ramadier
                    agreed; in fact, he agreed that our point of view was reasonable all along the
                    line. He told me that Leclerc has definitely turned down the Government’s
                    request to go to Indochina as High Commissioner and that he, Ramadier, had
                    offered the job only a few minutes before to General Juin,<note n="56"
                        xml:id="d86fn56">Gen. Alphonse Pierre Juin, Chief of the French Army General
                        Staff.</note> who promised to <pb facs="0088" n="74" xml:id="pg_74"/> think
                    it over and reply at an early date. Ramadier observed: “Of course no one wants
                    that job at this juncture, but I very much hope that Juin will take it”. (Juin
                    came out of Ramadier’s office as I went in).<note n="57" xml:id="d86fn57"
                        >Telegram 839, February 24, 2 p.m., from Paris, reported that General Juin
                        declined the offer (851G.00/2–2447).</note>
                </p>
                <p>Repeated London 136.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
